No code platforms usually have some kind of decent learning curve, some more than others. And if you want to integrate those platforms into other platforms, you’ve gotta know code. Or at least APIs and even more tools like Zapier.

The interesting thing to me is that the concept of no code feels like a lie. Yes, all of these platforms can build all kinds of products and businesses without code. But it’s at the expense of having to learn a whole new platform.

RT @GuillaumeMbh: $10 client: "Would it be possible to change your terms and conditions? We also need a discount btw"

$100,000 client: "Mo…

In a similar but somewhat unrelated note: I wish someone could explain / help me figure out how to properly get into crypto and NFTs so I can make some passive income. It’s just another thing that seems like it’s out of the reach of the average freelancer.

The average client looking for a business website (in my experience) can’t learn Webflow, which makes them rely on a developer yet again. Many clients are trying to get away from this, so they can operate without being stuck with a dev.

Most of the clients I end up working with (or even those I talk to about their startup / business dreams) want to be able to control their websites themselves and not be locked out by a developer or a platform that is confusing.

Many developers that I’ve spoken to don’t see SQSP as a no code platform. Which is odd to me, because in my book it’s the first no code platform that was truly 100% “no code”. You can build amazing websites in it. And it’s much easier to learn than Webflow.

I went to the first No Code Conference from Webflow a couple years back (pre-pandemic) and I was the only SQSP designer there. People looked at my name tag and saw SQSP and asked “what’s that?” or “are you cheating on Webflow?” Like it was sacrilege. Like how dare I go to this.
I know everything I know in web design from a drag and drop platform. So thinking about things code-first just isn’t doable for me. It actually makes my learning harder.
You don’t “need” to know code to excel in Webflow, but it helps immensely and builds upon fundamentals that you’d already know if you were a coder.

I really want to learn Figma and Webflow, and so many designers and developers just say “it’s easy, you don’t need to know code at all”. But the truth is that these platforms require a specific knowledge set that is made better by understanding code (primarily Webflow).

I feel like I need someone to pay me to learn Webflow and Figma, because every day I end up focusing on what’s actually making me money (Squarespace) instead of learning a new skill. It’s hard to invest in yourself when you’re not getting paid to learn.

It's pretty frustrating when you allow a company your personal information and they take it for granted, marketing to you when you explicitly say "I don't want this". It's basically them saying, we don't care, maybe you'll want this some day, so we'll keep it.

Another example: I signed up for Atom Finance over 2 years ago when they were beta testing a new app. Ended up not being for me, so I deleted my account entirely. I've continued to get emails since, and they don't allow you to unsubscribe. @atom_finance

SOME companies will tell you that they keep it on file just in case something catastrophic happens, but in the end, it's illegal for them to keep your email address after you've explicitly requested for it to be removed.

For example, I don't even have an E-Trade account anymore. I've unsubscribed multiple times over the years, and I just got an email from them telling me about Covid-19. I can't unsubscribe again, because I don't have an account.

Something that is revealed during a crisis / pandemic like this  a lot of people don't realize:
No matter how many times you unsubscribe, most companies will still keep your email address on file, illegally emailing you to let you know what they're doing during the crisis.
